citeinfo.title: Walla Walla Streams

descript.abstract: Channel network GIS layers are part of the general approach for assessing threats to the continued existence of Bull Trout, Spring Chinook and Summer Steelhead in the Walla Walla Watershed (Oregon), including all naturally spawned populations in the watershed.
descript.purpose: This layer is an intrinsic threat assessment tools for endangered salmon, specifically with regards to spawning and summer rearing habitat. The channel network data can be used to quantify available salmon habitat for these two different life stages.
descript.supplinf:
GIS channel network extraction and attribution
1.1 DEM and 10m Contours Source Data: USGS 1/3 Arc NED. Sink artifacts were eliminated from the merged DEMs using the Arcinfo GRID function FILL. Ten-meter vector-based contour data were assembled for the watershed.
1.2 Stream Channel Network Source Data: USGS NHD High Hydrography. Small intermittent streams were removed to prevent artificial variance of drainage densities.
1.3 Channel Gradient is calculated by intersecting the stream channel network with the 10-m contours. Channel reaches are defined by the intersection of the individual contours and by tributary junctions. Channel gradient for individual reaches are therefore calculated by taking the elevation difference between contour intervals divided by the length of channel for that reach. This vector-based approach is more robust and less error prone than exclusively DTM-orientated techniques.
1.4 Drainage Area was derived from the 1/3 NED DEM. The stream channel network was used to "burn" or deepen the elevation of the DEM, forcing the flow of water into these "canyons". The values of accumulated flow were then transfered to the upstream and downstream nodes of each arc and multiplied by the cell area.
